===============================================================================
    ON FAIRY CHESS PIECES

===============================================================================
==  0. Moves  =================================================================
===============================================================================

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
~~  0.0. Chess, viewed abstractly  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~



Chess is a deterministic, fully observable two-player game.  Let `C = {black,
white}` name the players.  Then the dynamics of chess is determined by its set
`P` of states, its transition relation `next : P --> Pow(P)`, its schedule
`turn : P --> C`, and its valuation `value : P --> Signs` where `Signs = {+inf,
-inf, 0}`.



We require a universal bound on `next`-chains' lengths; this occurs, for
instance, when `P` is finite and `next`'s transitive closure `~~>` is
anti-reflexive.  Then we may define `outcome : P --> Signs` by

    outcome(s) = (max if turn(p)==white else min) {outcome(q) : q in next(p)}
                 if value(p)==0 else value(p) 

Of great recreational interest is the computation of `outcome` on concrete
states of such as the 960 initial states designed by Bobby Fischer. 



We can say more about `(S, next, turn, value)` for chess.  If we ignore the
three kludgy FIDE rules regarding draw-by-repetition, castling, and pawn
double-moves, then each element of `P` is determined by its turn bit, its
plies-since-irreversible counter, and its array of pieces:

    P = C x [101] x (Grid --> ({empty} + C x Species)) 

Here, `Grid=[8]x[8]` and `Species = {pawn,knight,bishop,rook,queen,king}`.  Let
`turn, ply, get` project `P` to its components.  `value` is the sign of the
number of white kings minus the number of black kings on the board.  To recover
FIDE chess, we would also track the set of previous positions, six bits to
track which of the black and white rooks and kings have previously moved, and
which files if any are liable to en-passant. 



It remains to describe `next`.  To begin, let's ignore rules about moving into
check, edge effects on a finite board, and the specialness of the last rank for
pawn promotion.  Then `next(s)` is a union --- over `g in Grid` such that
`color(get(p)(g)) == turn(p)` --- of sets 

    {m(p) : (m,f) in movesof(species(cs))(color(cs), color.(get(p)))(g)} 
    where cs = get(s)(g)

What specifies these sets is a map `movesof : Species --> (C x (Grid --> C))
--> Grid --> Pow(P-->P)`.  We regard `movesof` as the essence of a chess
variant's dynamics.  In chess, `movesof` is equivariant to spatial translation,
to left-right reflection, and to the pairing of up-down reflection with color
inversion.  


~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
~~  0.1. Steps and Operators  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

So we are interested in atomic moves `(v,h) in Int x Nat`.  We have the binary
logical operators &, | and the unary slidification operator $(). 

We have 1.1 + 3.2 + 3.4 + 1.8 = 3.3.3 = 27 possible sliding/capture modes.

.-1      --- wazir
.-2      --- ferz
..-1     --- rook
..-2     --- bishop 
.-1.-2   --- mann (nonroyal king)
..-1..-2 --- queen
.^1-^2   --- peasant (unpromotable, nondoublemovable pawn)
.-5      --- knight
..-5     --- nightrider
..-2.-5  --- archbishop
..-1.-5  --- chancellor

